An Osun State Magistrates’ Court sitting in Ile-Ife on Monday remanded one Ibraheem Muhammed, 45, in Correctional Centre for fraudulently converting 22 cows to self. He however, pleaded not guilty to the three -count charge of breach of peace, threat to life and conversion and stealing preferred against him. The police prosecutor, Inspector Sunday Osanyintuyi, told the court that the defendant committed the offence on Jan 8, 2020 at Ile Funfun Area, Ile-Ife. Osanyintuyi said that the defendant converted 22 live cows valued #33 million that belonged to one Professor Olawoyin Adesiyan which was kept under his care as cattle rearer to his own use. He added that the defendant threatened one Idowu Ajayi, that he should never ask for his brother’s cows else he would have his life terminated. According to him, the defendant conducted himself in a manner likely to cause the breach of the peace by blackmailing Idowu Ajayi as thief. The Prosecutor stated further that the offence contravened 49(d), 86(1) and 383(8) sub section (b)  and 390 of the Criminal Code, Laws of Osun, 2002. Magistrate Joseph Owolawi did not grant the bail of the defendant, but ordered for his remand in Correctional Centre as he adjourned the case until January 21 for ruling on bail. 